bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: The Rockefeller Foundation was established by act of the New York State Legislature approved by the Governor on May 14, 1913, "to promote the well-being of mankind throughout the world." Between 1913 and 1928 the China Medical Board, the International Health Board, and the Division of Medical Education functioned as divisions of the Foundation, concentrating on the administration of programs in public health and medical education. A Division of Studies was created in 1923 to handle projects outside the medical field. These early years were experimental as the new foundation studied the methods of philanthropy and explored its relationships with other Rockefeller boards.

Although the Rockefeller Foundation is the largest and best known philanthropy founded by the Rockefeller family, it was neither the first nor the last to be established. The Rockefeller Institute for Medical Research (1901), the General Education Board (1902), the Rockefeller Sanitary Commission for the Eradication of Hookworm Disease (1909), and the Bureau of Social Hygiene (1911) all existed earlier. When the Foundation was created, the Sanitary Commission was disbanded. After the establishment of the Foundation, the Laura Spelman Rockefeller Memorial (1918) and the International Education Board (1923) were created.

The Rockefeller boards and their programs were reconsidered and reorganized in 1927-1928 in order to avoid overlapping programs. The International Health Board of the Foundation was disbanded and an International Health Division was organized. The China Medical Board, Inc., was established as a separately incorporated institution, and the China Medical Board of the Foundation ceased to exist. The Division of Studies was dropped and the Division of Medical Education was phased out. The Laura Spelman Rockefeller Memorial was combined with the Foundation and the Spelman Fund of New York was chartered to continue activities of the LSRM that were not absorbed by the Foundation. The International Education Board was disbanded.

As a result of this reorganization, the Foundation adopted a program which included public health work (administered by the IHD), the advancement of knowledge in the medical and natural sciences (in part taken over from the IEB), the social sciences (formerly the field of the LSRM), and the humanities and arts (shared with the GEB). The Rockefeller Institute and the Bureau of Social Hygiene were not affected by the reorganization. The program adopted by the Foundation at this time remained basically the same for the next twenty years.

As its files accumulated, the Foundation maintained a card index recording the names of institutional and individual grantees and correspondents. A microfilm copy of this index is available at the Archive Center.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The International Health Board of the Rockefeller Foundation maintained an office in Paris from 1917 as the headquarters for the work of the Commission for the Prevention of Tuberculosis in France. In 1922, anticipating the transfer of the tuberculosis work to the French, and the expansion of work in Europe, the Board agreed to share space and administrative expenses with the Rockefeller Foundation's Division of Medical Education. The Nursing Survey of the IHB was to be carried on from the same location. Other administrative units of the Foundation concerned with work in Europe used the same office.

The Paris office can be described as a colony of more or less independent units, occupying the same office space, loosely bound together under a chairman and a committee, both advisory in function, and sharing common services. The chairman of the Paris office exercised a general oversight, acting as advisor and coordinator. He was the representative of the President in Paris in the sense that he transmitted all general instruction from the central executives to the group while in the other direction he was spokesman for the group to New York. He had full Power of Attorney for all Rockefeller Foundation property in France. All bank accounts were in his name. He called together and presided over the Paris officers in committees for discussions of mutual problems and in consultation with them either agreed to or rejected their various fellowships and grants-in-aid dockets, his signature being required, as well as that of the Comptroller and divisional representative concerned, on all Paris office grants. Chairmen of the Paris office before World War II were Selskar M. Gunn, 1922-1932, George K. Strode, 1932-1938, A. J. Warren, 1938-1939, Selskar M. Gunn, 1939-1940.

The office committee, which corresponded roughly to the staff conference in New York, had no legal status whatever yet acquired with the years a definite function. All officers' actions or grants-in-aid, grants for deposed scholars, and fellowships passed through this committee. Here, questions of general policy were discussed.

Officers in divisions in Paris had an integrity and autonomy unknown in New York, that granted by sheer remoteness from the main office. From fund allocated by directors in New York for expenditure in Europe, officers had the power of independent action without reference to New York, limited however to grants-in-aid and fellowships of not more than one year and $3,000.

The Paris office was the fiscal agent of the New York office with respect to European affairs. The Paris office administered payments under appropriations made by the Trustees in New York for European projects. The Comptroller also administered payments under officers actions in Paris, and acted as fiscal agent for the General Education Board and for the national councils with respect to fellows assigned to Europe for study.

The Administrator of the Paris office was charged with the non-divisional functions of the office, i.e., personnel, office quarters, equipment, central services, travel, purchasing, etc. The budget was made up in two sections, the principal part in francs, the lesser in dollars.

Divisions represented at the Paris office before World War II were the International Health Board, later the International Health Division, the Division of Studies, the Division of Medical Education, the Medical Sciences Division, the Divisions of Natural and social Sciences. Officers assigned to the Paris office included F. Elisabeth Crowell, E. E. Day, Alan Gregg, Selskar M. Gunn, Lauder Jones, Tracey B. Kittredge, Robert A. Lambert, H. M. Miller, Daniel P. O'Brien, Richard M. Pearce, F. F. Russell, George K. Strode, Wilbur E. Tisdale, John Van Sickle, George E. Vincent, A. J. Warren and Warren Weaver.

In 1941 the Paris office closed for the duration of the war. The space was used for a time by an agency of the Vichy Government under the direction of Dr. Alexis Carrell, and the Foundation's work in Europe was continued by the newly formed Rockefeller Foundation Health Commission. One staff member, the Comptroller, Robert Letort, a native Frenchman, remained on the payroll looking after the Foundation's interests. In 1945 Letort and Charles N. Leach, a member of the RHC, reopened the office. It remained open until 1959, but its functions and character were completely changed. It became a place maintained for the convenience of a small group of officers assigned more or less permanently to Paris and for the convenience also of the somewhat larger group who used Paris as a base for European travel. It still had a chairman with whom the New York office, usually through the vice president, corresponded on questions of general policy. Only two divisions, Medical Sciences and International Health Division, maintained permanent staff. The Paris office postwar had no funds for allocation of grants-in-aid and fellowships. These were administered from New York. Except for payments to French projects, all appropriations to European projects were now paid from New York. The Staff maintained services such as filing and bookkeeping and provided secretarial service. Personnel assigned to the Paris office in the postwar period included Johannes H. Bauer, Elizabeth W. Brackett, Robert P. Burden, John B. Grant, Frederick C. Lane, Charles N. Leach, John Maier, H. M. Miller, Daniel P. O'Brien, Paul Russell, R. Rolf Struthers, Mary E. Tennant. Chairmen of the Paris office were Rolf Struthers, 1946-1954, and John Maier, 1954-1959.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: The files of the Paris office have been sorted and weeded several times over the years. What remains is a far from complete record. The arrangement, however, is as received, that is, these files have not been processed through the New York office but have been in dead storage since shipment from France. The filing system has not been altered.

relatedmaterial.head: Related Materials
relatedmaterial.p: Records related to those of the Paris office include minutes of meetings of the Paris office committee which can be found in Record Group 3, Administration, Program and Policy, Series 904 Officers Conferences. Program and policy reports relevant to Paris office administration are 900 Org. 33, 900 Org. 36, 900 Pro. 16. There is also material in Record Group 1.1, Projects, Series 700, European Office Administration, and Series 500, France.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Programs included are Medical Sciences (MS), Natural Sciences (NS), International Health Division (IHD), Social Sciences (SS). Correspondence is mainly between Europeans, grantees and others, and divisional officers in the Paris office. Subjects are public health, institutes of public health, neurology, physiology, nursing, biology, psychiatry. Correspondents include Arne Tiselius, Jean Piaget, Hugh Cairns, Alan Gregg, F. Elizabeth Crowell. There is correspondence in French and German. There is a section designated "General" which includes non-divisional correspondence, and a section for League of Nations correspondence.

arrangement.head: Arrangement note
arrangement.p: Files in three subseries (correspondence, financial material, reports) numbered continuously. Correspondence is arranged by program, within program alphabetically by country, within country alphabetically by title (person, subject, or institution). Strict chronological arrangement is followed within folders, reports and reprints are filed with correspondence unless numbers or dimensions necessitated a second folder. Files may include grants, general correspondence, declinations, or fellowships all in the same folder, that is, all correspondence with a given person or institution is general filed together regardless of its nature.

relatedmaterial.head: Related Archival Materials note
relatedmaterial.p: Related material can be found in the Rockefeller Foundation's Projects files, RG 1.1, under European country numbers, especially 500 France and 700 Europe.

Correspondence is mainly between Europeans, grantees and others, and divisional officers in the Paris office. Subjects are public health, institutes of public health, neurology, physiology, nursing, biology, psychiatry. Correspondents include Arne Tiselius, Jean Piaget, Hugh Cairns, Alan Gregg, F. Elizabeth Crowell. There is correspondence in French and German. There is a section designated "General" which includes non-divisional correspondence, and a section for League of Nations correspondence.

Correspondence is arranged by program, within program alphabetically by country, within country alphabetically by title (person, subject, or institution). Strict chronological arrangement is followed within folders, reports and reprints are filed with correspondence unless numbers or dimensions necessitated a second folder. Files may include grants, general correspondence, declinations, or fellowships all in the same folder, that is, all correspondence with a given person or institution is general filed together regardless of its nature.

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: From 1935 to 1973, the New Delhi Field Office of the Rockefeller Foundation (RF) administered cooperative programs throughout India in the fields of medicine and public health (1935-1973), agriculture (1956-73), and the humanities and social sciences (1964-72). The New Delhi office also served as the RF's Far Eastern regional headquarters, replacing Shanghai temporarily from 1942 to 1946 and permanently after 1949. Between 1949 and 1952, the office was located in Bangalore.

The New Delhi office was headed by the Field Director or Foundation Representative in India, who served as a scientist-cum-administrator and reported to the appropriate division director in New York. His staff included an Assistant Field Director, staff scientists and research assistants, and local administrative personnel. The field office staff was continually augmented by visiting specialists from around the world. By 1966, the fifteen-member staff in New Delhi constituted the largest RF contingent outside New York.

The RF's International Health Division (IHD) had established the first office in New Delhi for the purpose of extending its India hookworm control program, which had begun in the Madras Presidency in 1920. Subsequent medical and public health activities in India included malaria control, the development of demonstration health units, nursing education, nutrition studies, and, increasingly throughout the 1950s and 1960s, medical education and research. Significant grants went to the All India Institute of Hygiene and Public Health in Calcutta (1913-50) and the Virus Research Center at Poona (1951-71). Grants also supported the Indian Council for Medical Research and the All India Institute of Medical Sciences (1952-1973).

The last year in which grants were made in the medical field from the New Delhi office was 1970. At that time, the RF's Medical and Natural Sciences division separated into two distinct disciplines, Biomedical Sciences and Natural and Environmental Sciences.

The RF's agricultural work in India officialy began in 1956 when the Government of India and the RF signed a Memorandum of Understanding. This agreement created the Indian Agricultural Program (IAP) and spread the so-called Green Revolution to India. The IAP was the fourth in a series of ambitious "country" programs in agriculture begun by the RF in Mexico (1943) and subsequently extended to Colombia (1950) and Chile (1955). Its purpose was twofold: to increase cereal crop production through the development of high-yielding seed, and to strengthen graduate education in agriculture. Under the Memorandum of Understanding, the Government of India arranged for the necessary land and facilities and budget for local staff, while the RF provided a permanent staff of resident specialists and appropriated annual sums for equipment and other expenses incurred by the field programs. The Foundation also made grants to selected agricultural institutions and to Indian scientists to pursue research in the United States.

Research and postgraduate training were viewed as interrelated activities. In 1958, with the Foundation's support, a postgraduate school was inaugurated at the Indian Agricultural Research Institute, New Delhi (est. 1905), with the authority to award the M.Sc. and Ph.D. degrees. After 1960, new legislation made possible the creation of several state agricultural universities modeled after American land-grant universities. These universities developed relationships with the various crop improvement programs and offered valuable research opportunities for American and Indian agronomists.

The All India Coordinated Cereal Improvement Projects, the backbone of the IAP research program, represented a new approach to crop research in India. Sponsored by the Indian Council of Agricultural Research (ICAR) and jointly operated by the ICAR and state institutions, each project studies the agronomy, entomology, pathology, genetics, and breeding of an individual crop. For the first time, research stations and substations were established throughout the subcontinent in order to coordinate research activities across the major agro-climatic zones. The programs began with maize in 1957 (although maize work had begun in India in 1945) and came to include sorghum and other millets (1957), wheat (1961), and rice (1965). Notable increases occurred in wheat production with the importation in 1965 of dwarf materials from Mexico. In conducting seed development research, the IAP benefited from the expertise of those RF agronomists who had served first in Mexico, namely Edwin J. Wellhausen, Ulysses J. Grant, Ernest W. Sprague, and the 1970 Nobel Prize winner, Norman E. Borlaug. Allied areas of research included drainage, fertility, soil and water management, and agricultural economics.

In 1973, the RF decided to bring to a close its Indian Agricultural Program. India continued to carry out crop improvement work, utilizing the administrative, teaching, and research structures jointly established over seventeen years by the IAP and the Government of India. The RF therefore phased out its involvement in all improvement programs except rice, which was continued until 1975 by Wayne H. Freeman at Hyderabad. From 1976 to 1983, the Hyderabad office under Leland R. House operated the International Crops Research Institute for the Semi-Arid Tropics (ICRISAT). This institute functioned as part of the Foundation's "Conquest of Hunger" program, which had been formally established in 1963.

In October 1964, Chadbourne Gilpatric took up residence in India as Visiting Professor in Philosophy at Delhi University, with responsibilities for representing RF interests in the Humanities and Social Sciences (HSS). Under HSS director Joseph E. Black (1964-70), Gilpatric sought to advance research and teaching in the humanities and in the social and hard sciences. He was particularly eager to strengthen curriculum at agricultural universities and to increase and preserve library holdings. From 1968 to 1972, Gilpatric coordinated a socioeconomic study of small farmers in Uttar Pradesh state. Gilpatric returned to the United States in April 1972. The Social Sciences programs had been officially phased out in 1970 and replaced with separate Arts and Humanities divisions.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The New Delhi Field Office records (RG 6.7) of the Rockefeller Foundation Archives document the operation of the office and the programs it administered in the medical, agricultural, and social sciences. The records span the dates 1935-76, but ninety percent of the record group dates from the period 1956-73 and relates to the Indian Agricultural Program (IAP), operated by the RF's Natural Sciences and Agriculture Division. The IAP records provide a comprehensive account of the RF's role in establishing an international collaborative program of technical assistance. They also constitute an important source for the study of the history of modern agriculture and agricultural education in India.

Four folders of photographs were removed from Record Group 6.7 during processing and added to the Photograph Collection of the Archive Center. scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Subgroup I, Series 1, General Administrative Files (1952-1976), contains correspondence and miscellaneous materials pertaining to general field office operations. Correspondence is arranged alphabetically by subject. Filed under "Government of India" are copies of agreements and understandings (1957-1976) reached between the RF and the Indian government. The bulk of the Government of India correspondence consists of letters between the field office, government ministries, and New York headquarters concerning Indian government procedures for proposing and clearing grants to agencies or institutions in India. It also covers procedures for reporting renewals, extensions, or amendments of fellowships; sending dollar checks to the United States; and preparing income tax reports. Additional correspondence concerns budgetary matters, field office bank accounts, employee housing, and staffing of the American International School, where RF staff enrolled their children.

Other material in Series 1 is filed under the heading "Operating Records" and fills boxes 7-21. Operating records include customs clearance permits, leases for rented offices and apartments in New Delhi, personnel policy files, record-keeping procedures, and inventories of imported field equipment.

arrangement.p: Correspondence is arranged alphabetically by subject.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Subgroup I, Series 2, IAP Administrative Files, includes correspondence, minutes, program development files, and fellowship and scholarship files (1950-1975) relating to the planning and review of the IAP research programs and to international programs with which the Foundation collaborated.

Field office correspondence with New York headquarters, the Indian Council of Agricultural Research (ICAR), and the Ministry of Food and Agricultural fills boxes 22 through 25. Correspondence with the New York office relates to travel, staffing needs, funding, equipment and supplies, and seed shipments. Letters between IAP field directors and the Directors General of the ICAR, Dr. B. P. Pal and Dr. A. B. Joshi, pertain to meetings and workshops, crop programs, research evaluations and publications.

Correspondence with representatives of international organizations and agencies is arranged alphabetically by country or name of organization and fills boxes 29 through 33. Letters concern agriculture assistance programs undertaken by other organizations, as well as preparations for IAP staff visits to countries outside India. As a whole, the correspondence reveals the international network of technical know-how brought to bear upon improving Asian agriculture between 1958 and 1973.

The program development files in Series 2 contain influential reports on RF agricultural policy and Indian agriculture. These include a statement by RF Director Warren Weaver, "The Program in the Natural Sciences," prepared in 1950, one year before the creation of the Natural Sciences and Agriculture Division. Also present is a 1951 memorandum from Weaver to Dr. Richmond K. Anderson, the RF Representative in India, in which Weaver outlines procedures for referring to New York Indian requests for information on agricultural grants. Also of interest is the 1952 report, "Notes on Indian Agriculture," by J. G. Harrar, Paul C. Mangelsdorf, and Warren Weaver. This report led to several follow-up visits by RF representatives and ultimately to India's request for a collaborative agricultural program.

arrangement.head: Arrangement note
arrangement.p: Records are arranged alphabetically by type of material from "Correspondence" through "Program development files." These files are followed by International Development Programs, International Organizations, and United States Agencies.
Correspondence with representatives of international organizations and agencies is arranged alphabetically by country or name of organization.

relatedmaterial.head: Related Archival Materials note
relatedmaterial.p: Additional material on international collaboration is contained in Series 4, Crop Improvement Programs, and Series 6, Agricultural Research Institutes. Series 4 includes information on the Inter-Asian Corn Improvement Program (1963-1973), other international maize assistance programs (1961-1971), and the IRRI (International Rice Research Institute) (1967-1973). Correspondence relating to CIMMYT (Centro International de Mejoramiento de Maiz y Trigo) and its cooperation with the All India Maize and Wheat programs is contained in Series 6, Subseries 3.
Additional reports on Indian agriculture are located in Record Group 1.1 (Projects), Series 464 (India).

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Series 3 contains the daily office diaries of IAP Field Directors Ralph W. Cummings (1957-1966), Guy B. Baird (1959-1971), Ordway Starnes (1971-1973), and RF Representative Wayne H. Freeman (1974-1975). These diaries provide a nearly unbroken account of the writers' administrative and scientific activities, constituting a unique source of information and commentary. Diary entries were generally hand-written and then typed by an assistant. The field office retained a copy, and the original type-written copy was sent to New York with one or two carbon copies for filing in other office correspondence. Thus, excerpts of these diaries appear in Record Group 1.1 (Projects) and 1.2 (Projects) and occasionally in Record Group 2 (General Correspondence).

arrangement.head: Arrangement note
arrangement.p: Alphabetically arranged by author.

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access
accessrestrict.p: Officers' diaries are open for scholarly research provided that (1) the diarist is deceased and (2) the volume to be examined is at least twenty years old. All reasonable efforts will be made to determine the fate of the diarist(s), but if such efforts are fruitless then the material will remain closed to scholarly research until 100 years after the officer's year of birth.

did.unittitle: Indian Agricultural Program - Crop Improvement Programs

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Series 4, Crop Improvement Programs, is the largest of the series in Subgroup I (boxes 39 to 94) and contains the records of the All India Coordinated Crop Improvement programs, the seed development program, and miscellaneous food study programs.

Certain types of records are common to Subseries 1 through 6. Correspondence relating to the establishment and organization of the particular program appears first within each subseries. Substantial correspondence exists for maize (1957-72), millet (1965-68, 1970-71), rice (1964-83), sorghum (1957-73), wheat (1965-73), and seed development (1959-73). Correspondence of a miscellaneous character follows, treating such technical matters as experiment station operations, equipment maintenance, conference and workshop scheduling, training programs, relations with other agricultural organizations, and research programs in seed collection, breeding, entomology and pathology.

Correspondence is typically followed by unpublished and published reports summarizing the results of experimental tests. These reports are arranged alphabetically by corporate author in Subseries 1, Maize, and alphabetically by title throughout the rest of the series. Filed with unpublished reports are manuscript drafts of reports on various aspects of the research programs. Also present are "trip reports" written by staff from the field.

Published materials include the annual Progress Reports of the various All India Coordinated Crop Improvement Programs, conference proceedings, special reports, Foundation reports, monographs, periodicals, and offprints.

arrangement.head: Arrangement note
arrangement.p: The series is arranged in ten subseries:

Subseries 1 - Maize Subseries 2 - Millet Subseries 3 - Rice Subseries 4 - Seed Development Subseries 5 - Sorghum Subseries 6 - Wheat Subseries 7 - Miscellaneous IAP Staff Projects Subseries 8 - Miscellaneous Food, Crop, and Study Programs Subseries 9 - USAID Projects Under Public Law 480 Subseries 10 - Miscellaneous Reports
Within subseries, records are arranged alphabetically by subject or type of material and thereunder chronologically.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Subseries 1 (boxes 102-110) relates exclusively to the establishment and operation of the IARI Post Graduate School; it is divided into general correspondence and postgraduate school correspondence. General correspondence includes the office correspondence (1957-1973) of the IARI Director B. P. Pal; however, the bulk of the correspondence pertains to the IARI Department of Farm Operation and Management. This department provided farming service to the field work of all IARI divisions. These services included land preparation, irrigation, and machinery operation and maintenance. Among the correspondents are IARI directors B. P. Pal, A. B. Joshi, M. S. Swaminathan, and K. Kanungo, and Foundation Field Directors Ralph Cummings, Guy B. Baird, and Ordway Starnes.

Postgraduate school correspondence (1956-1973) relates to the administration and organization of the school, in which IAP Field Director, Ralph W. Cummings played a leading role. He began discussions with IARI faculty and staff in January 1957 and served as the school's Acting Dean from 1959-1960. He was succeeded in 1960 by A. B. Joshi.

Interfiled within the correspondence are minutes of faculty meetings and academic council meetings. Additional correspondence pertains to student eligibility for RF assistantships at IARI (1961-1973) and to academic divisions (1956-1973), especially Agricultural Engineering, Agricultural Physics, Farm Operations and Management, Genetics, and the Water Technology Centre.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Records in Subgroup II, Medical and Natural Sciences Program, offer evidence of the RF's increasing support for medical education and public health, recognized by the creation in 1951 of the Division of Medicine and Public Health (MEPH).

Early in 1951, a Virus Research Center was established in Poona in cooperation with the Indian Council of Medical Research. Files retained by the New Delhi office document the center's establishment, administration, and research program. They are located in Series 3.

In October 1951, Dr. J. Austin Kerr arrived to organize and direct the Virus Research Center. Kerr's correspondence and that of his successor, Telford H. Work, is filed under "Director's office correspondence." This correspondence fills nine folders and is arranged in groupings designated by the field office: New York office, New Delhi office, Indian Council of Medical Research, and colleagues in India. Files include both incoming and outgoing correspondence with these other offices and individuals.

Research centered on the identification and isolation of Indian viruses transmitted by blood-sucking arthropods. Files relating to individual viruses are arranged by virus name. Interim activity reports (1952-1957) provide information on ongoing virus work. The Calcutta School of Tropical Medicine and the Indian Veterinary Research Institute at Izatnagar participated in the research effort; correspondence between Poona and these institutions is filed at the end of Series 3.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The records (1960-1978) of the Rockefeller Foundation's Cali, Colombia field office, consisting of routine administrative correspondence, document to a limited extent the administration of the RF's Education for Development (EFD) program and other programs undertaken in Colombia by the RF's divisions of Medical and Natural Sciences and Humanities and Social Sciences.

While the focus of the Bogota office was agriculture, the Cali office coordinated programs in rural, community, and university development. Series I contains eight folders concerning the Cali field station of the RF's Virus Research Program (1964-73), a program for research on arthropod-borne (arbo) viruses. The bulk of the collection, located in Series II and III, relates to the development of the University del Valle's Academic and library programs and its medical school under the auspices of the RF's University Development (1963-74) and Education For Development (1974-78) programs. Series IV includes correspondence between the Cali staff and several American universities cooperating with the Universidad del Valle in rural and tropical disease research, preventitive medicine and nutrition, and child and public health.

Correspondents include Farzam Arbab, Ulysses J. Grant, Guy S. Hayes, Robert S. Morison, Patrick N. Owens, Dorothy Parker, Virgil C. Scott, Harold Trapido, John Veenstra, and John M. Weir. Some correspondence is in Spanish.

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: The Rockefeller Foundation opened a field office in Cali, Colombia in 1960, ten years after the establishment of the Colombian Agricultural Program in Bogota. Guy S. Hayes, an Assistant Director in the Medical and Natural Sciences division, held the post of Field Director in Cali from 1960 until 1970. After 1970, the office was headed by Foundation Representatives Patrick N. Owens (1970-1974) and Farzam Arbab (1974-78). The office closed on December 31, 1983.

RF activity in Colombia reflected the broad reorientation of Foundation programming away from Europe and towards the developing world which took place under RF Presidents Dean Rusk (1952-1961) and J. George Harrar (1961-1972). In Latin America, as in Africa and Southeast Asia, the Foundation sought to relieve basic human needs by establishing rural and community development programs, strengthening disease research facilities, and revitalizing universities that they might become more responsive to local populations. The RF approach to development involved the training of local personnel and the strengthening of local institutions through exchange programs with American universities and fellowships support for Colombian scholars.

One of the prime beneficiaries of RF support in Colombia was the Universidad del Valle and its Medical School at Cali, which received assistance under the RF's University Development program (1963-1978). (The program was renamed Education for Development (EFD) in 1974). The Universidad del Valle became one of the best medical schools in Latin America, combining the practice of public health at the Candelaria Rural Health Center with the teaching and practice of medicine. The EFD program was phased out in 1978, with future university grants made within the appropriate RF program areas.

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: In 1943 the Rockefeller Foundation and the Mexican government established a cooperative program to improve Mexican food crop production. The program had a dual nature: the qualitative/quantitative betterment of the basic food crops of Mexico, and a parallel teaching/outreach program designed to broaden local and national agricultural education. As a result the RF and Mexican government agencies and universities sponsored dozens of joint projects that stressed inter-American agricultural cooperation. Crop improvement programs for maize, wheat, and rice were included, as well as weed control and fisheries projects.

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: The Mideast Wheat Research and Training program was a project funded by the Rockefeller Foundation to help with crop research and agricultural production in Turkey. The program included breeding of adapted varieties of both spring and winter wheat for various ecological conditions, training for wheat scientists from cooperating countries, and advice and assistance in the development of the local research and production programs. In September 1967 the Rockefeller and Turkey began negotiations for the Rockefeller Foundation to participate in the development of the national wheat program. By July 1, 1970, the Turkish Wheat Research and Training Center had been established. The Rockefeller Foundation agreed to a start-up grant of $100,000, which was to expire at the end of 1968. Rockefeller Foundation funding was extended and renewed through the 1970s. In 1977 the Rockefeller Foundation signed a final three-year extension.
Quality was not considered important at the start of the project. Rather, the point was to produce a large amount of wheat. The project pioneered an approach to the problem of a specific crop.

There were several issues with the Wheat Research Project that quickly became apparent. Initially, only fluent English speakers were eligible for overseas training. As the program developed, staff received English language instruction before going for training, but once abroad they required additional training in order to function effectively and produce. Relations with the Turkish government were also complicated, and issues arose with organization and method. There were also struggles with various governmental departments. These issues were not helped by Turkey's bureaucracy and climate of administrative instability, attributable to constantly changing governments.
Over thirteen years Turkish wheat production increased from around 10 million metric tons to 17 million with general agreement that this increase was largely owing to the wheat improvement project.

Various names were used to refer to the Wheat Research and Training Program, including: Middle East Wheat Improvement Project, Wheat Improvement Project, Wheat Research Program, Mid-East Wheat Research and Training Center, and Ankara Field Office.
Significant staff members include: Ahmet Demirlicakmak, Charles K. Mann, E. E. Saari, Jon Michael Prescott, and Bill C. Wright.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Mideast Wheat Research and Training Project records contain general correspondence and administrative documents pertaining to the Turkish wheat stations and the various foundations and institutions connected to wheat research in Turkey during the 1970s. Correspondence, reports, and printed material detail the Center's wheat research work and plant breeding and its interactions with Turkish authorities and with other agricultural institutes and university agronomists. This collection documents the day-to-day work of the Center; for materials regarding the establishment and administration of the Wheat Research Center one should consult the files on Turkish Wheat Research in the Rockefeller Foundation project files, RG 1, Accession 83, Series 105 (804).
